Trump and the Economy
NEW YORK – Financial markets finally woke up to the reality that Trump is the US president.
The world has endured two years of Trump's unfiltered tweets and public statements as the most powerful man in the world, so the obvious question is, what kept things going for so long?
On one hand, until now, investors have given Trump the benefit of the doubt, expecting him to deliver on his promises.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies that benefit corporations and shareholders, they are willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many believe that in the end, "the adults in the room" will constrain Trump to ensure that government policies do not go off course.
This assumption was more or less borne out during Trump's first year in office, a period when economic growth and expectations of corporate profit growth – thanks to impending tax cuts and deregulation – fueled strong stock market performance.
In 2017, U.S. stock indices rose by over 20%.
But in 2018, things took a sharp turn, especially in the final months.
While corporate profits increased by more than 20% (thanks to the tax cuts), the U.S. stock market oscillated for most of the year and then fell sharply.
Currently, all indices are in correction territory (down 10% from recent highs), with tech-heavy indices like the Nasdaq falling into bear market territory (down 20% or more).
While the increase in market volatility reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turmoil is due to Trump.
At the start of this year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which pushed up long-term interest rates and brought an economy already close to full employment to a fever pitch.
In February, worries about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve’s target of 2% triggered the first risk-off episode of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important US trading partners.
Market concerns about government protectionist policies have risen and fallen all year but are now reaching new heights.
Recent US actions against China seem poised to spark a full-scale trade, economic, and geo-political cold war.
Another concern is that Trump’s other policies could have stagflationary effects (weaker growth and rising inflation).
After all, Trump intends to limit foreign direct investment inflows and implement broad immigration restrictions, which will drag on labor supply growth at a time when the aging workforce and skill mismatches are becoming more acute.
In addition, the Trump administration has yet to propose infrastructure programs to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
In tweets and other venues, Trump continuously criticizes businesses' hiring, production, investment, and pricing behaviors, especially those of tech companies, which already face widespread opposition and increasingly intense competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also been hit by US policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening have raised both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies have experienced capital flight and appreciation of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily dependent on exports have suffered due to falling commodity prices, while even those with indirect trade ties to China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy has created volatility.
The US reinstatement of sanctions on Iran raised oil prices, which subsequently fell after the US government revoked exemptions and pressured Saudi Arabia to increase oil production.
While US consumers benefit from low oil prices, energy company stocks cannot sustain this.
Moreover, excessive price fluctuations are bad for both producers and consumers because they hinder wise investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, it now appears that almost all the benefits of last year's tax cuts have flowed to the corporate sector rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means that household consumption may soon slow down, further impacting the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent plunge in US and global stock markets was Trump's own words and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (although he recently reached a "truce" with Chinese President Xi Jinping), was Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve. His criticism began in spring 2018 when US economic growth was above 4%.
Due to these earlier criticisms, the market became jumpy when the Fed raised interest rates this month and signaled a slower pace of hikes in 2019.
It is more likely that the Fed's relatively hawkish stance was a reaction to Trump's criticism of it.
Facing hostile tweets from President Trump, Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell needs to signal that the central bank remains politically independent.
But then, because Congress refused to fund his useless border wall with Mexico, Trump decided to shut down part of the federal government.
This put the market in a state of near panic, and as the shutdown dragged on, reports emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell – which could turn a correction into a crash.
Just before Christmas, US Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to issue a public statement to reassure the markets.
He declared that Trump had no plans to fire Powell, and that the US fiscal situation was good, which only highlighted the question of whether things really were good.
And recent changes in personnel within the government that do not affect economic decisions have also caused market concern.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Secretary of Defense James Mattis are set to leave, leaving no sound minds in Trump's cabinet.
What remains will all be economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks, following Trump's lead.
The possibility of a full-scale geo-political conflict with China still cannot be ruled out at this point.
A new cold war could lead to de-globalization, disrupting global supply chains, but the tech industry will bear the brunt, as evidenced by the recent cases against ZTE and Huawei.
Meanwhile, Trump seems determined to undermine the EU and NATO's cohesion when Europe's economy and politics are already unstable.
The special prosecutor Robert Mueller’s investigation into Trump’s 2016 campaign’s ties to Russia looms over his presidency like a Damocles sword.
Trump is now the financial markets’ Dr. Strangelove.
Like the paranoid lunatic in Stanley Kubrick’s classic film, he is trapped in a cycle of mutually assured economic destruction.
Today, the market sees this danger, and the risks of a financial crisis and global recession are rising.
